+# Chapter 7
+
+Late June, 1998
+
+Mira reached the greenhouse at 5:40 a.m., just before sunrise, when the glass still held the night's cold. Arun was already there, sorting seed trays in silence beside the blue pot Nani had painted with white cranes the year before she died.
+
+"You came," he said.
+
+She told him she had not slept. The letter from her mother had arrived at 11:40 p.m., folded twice, sealed with the chapel wax, and with it came the old dread she thought she had outgrown.
+
+Arun asked whether the letter mentioned Elias.
+
+"No," Mira said, and then, because the lie sat badly in her mouth, she added, "Not by name. She only wrote, 'the one who went missing by the river.'"
+
+Outside, Hush Road was still dark. A logging truck passed east, then another, both of them leaving a shiver in the greenhouse glass.
+
+Arun handed her a tin cup of tea. "Then today is only about the garden," he said.
+
+Mira wanted to believe him, but her hands shook when she took the cup.
+
+On the workbench, beside the twine and the rusted scissors, lay the silver key she had found under the chapel floorboards when she was thirteen. She had started carrying it again three nights ago.
+
+"You kept it," Arun said.
+
+"I never threw it away."
+
+He looked at her more sharply then. "Your mother said Elias ran. Mine said he drowned. Nani was the only one who ever said neither."
+
+Mira slipped the key into her apron pocket. Through the far pane she could see the path leading toward Saint Alder Chapel, pale with dust already. For a second she remembered another June morning, ten years earlier, Elias standing in that same path with wet cuffs and a bloodied knuckle, telling her not to tell anyone what he had seen in the toll house ledger.
+
+"We should go before the bells," she said.
+
+Arun set the last seed tray aside. At 6:05 a.m. they closed the greenhouse, left the blue pot on the sill, and started toward the chapel carrying the letter, the key, and the names neither of them wanted to say aloud.
